column9: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen. Posts include statuses, photos, links, videos and more. (Unique Users)

‚ÄúI will say that my intentions are to treat these as moments of time, specifically focusing on people of color...I wanted ‚ÄòDamaged Goods‚Äô to be about following this group of friends, whether it‚Äôs seeing them going to the club, or working on their art, or seeing them in the workplace. I think it‚Äôs revolutionary itself to just see people of color living. As a gay black filmmaker, me creating art is revolutionary in itself.‚Äù

Co-writer and star Kyra Jones on why they wrote about dating apps: ‚ÄúTheoretically, online dating should be a level playing field because you all have your bio to write, you all get the same amount of pictures, you get the same shot at making a good first impression...But it's still not level because there are still so many identity issues that go into who is seen as desirable.‚Äù

#OTVTonight 2019 Preshow & BTS

A note from OTV founder and Head of Development, Aymar Jean Christian:

#OTVTonight is a wrap and my heart is full! Last week's screening was more proof that Chicago artists are making the best indie TV in the country and representing our diversity more than any channel in Hollywood -- in front of and behind the camera! 

Don't believe me? Come see for yourself as the projects premiere online and in Chicago during #OTVWednesdays this spring: http://facebook.com/weareotv/events

First I want to thank the Museum of Contemporary Art Chicago for hosting us for the third year in a row, and to January Parkos Arnall, Christy LeMaster and the entire public programs team. We're so very grateful to the Chicago Reader, Free Write Arts & Literacy, Humboldt House, Mainstream Media, LLC, and People Who Care for partnering with us to make this happen. 

Eli Micky and Jenna Anast deserve a big round of applause for producing this event, with Elijah also designing our beautiful set! Many thanks to Chris Walker and Ahlaam Delange for providing essential support, and to Elsa Medhin, Dio Aldridge, Kinidee Lanier, Alex Advocaat, and Lena Elmeligy for their assistance in the production.

I'm so lucky to have had Hijo Pr√≥digo back as our DJ who keeps us bopping during our pre-show, post-show and commercial breaks, and Karla Huffman-Barry gave me life during our trap yoga intermission! 

Finally, thank you to the teams behind The Right Swipe, Damaged Goods, FOBia Series, and #goodenoughtv and our esteemed moderators Sam Bailey, Fatimah Asghar, Isaac Gomez, and Eva Saha Daniel for bringing your brilliance to OTV!

The future of TV is intersectional!

Sam Bailey and Fatimah Asghar, co-creators of #BrownGirlsTV and executive producers of the upcoming Damaged Goods, talk about why director Vincent Martell's series matters to WBEZ! 

"We want to do something that feels very real but also has a bit of surrealism and play, because we‚Äôre still experimenting as artists. So not only are we telling this story about a bunch of these different identities, but I also want to give these creators room to play in their filmmaking." - Sam Bailey

"The idea of a web series and the digital platform offered a sense of freedom. It was a way in which we didn‚Äôt have to ask permission for the stories we were telling ‚Ä¶ and really, it was because there was no other way." - Fatimah Asghar
